## Rules content

### Framework selection — mandatory pytest

Apply when choosing or reviewing a Python test stack for any package in this repository.

- Knowledge: Top-five candidates scored against repo requirements (fixtures, async, parametrization, plugins, CI/IDE support, ecosystem, maintainability) — max 10 per row, total 50.

| Framework | Fixtures | Async | Parametrize | Plugins/CI | Ecosystem | Total |
|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|
| **pytest** (selected) | 10 | 10 | 10 | 10 | 10 | **50** |
| unittest (stdlib) | 5 | 6 | 4 | 8 | 9 | 32 |
| hypothesis | 7 | 8 | 10 | 7 | 7 | 39 |
| nose2 | 6 | 5 | 6 | 4 | 3 | 24 |
| robot framework | 4 | 3 | 5 | 6 | 5 | 23 |

- Rule: **pytest** is the mandatory and only approved Python test runner — do not introduce unittest class suites, nose, nose2, or robot framework unless the user explicitly requests a migration plan.
- Rule: Async tests use **pytest-asyncio** with `asyncio_mode = "auto"` in `[tool.pytest.ini_options]`.
- Rule: Property-based tests may use **hypothesis** as a pytest plugin only — never as a replacement runner.
- Rule: Declare `pytest`, `pytest-asyncio`, and optional `httpx` (HTTP integration) in the package `pyproject.toml` `dependency-groups.dev` or `[project.optional-dependencies].dev`.
- Rule: Use plain `assert` with clear messages; avoid heavyweight custom assertion libraries unless already adopted in the package.

### Test roots and layout — one concern per file

Apply when scaffolding or extending tests for a Python deliverable.

- Knowledge: Every Python package must have a dedicated test root — microservices use `tests/`; uv tools and client libraries use `testing/`.

| Package kind | Test root | Unit | Integration | User-case | Shared fixtures |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| gRPC microservice (`*.svc/server/`) | `tests/` | `tests/unit/` | `tests/integration/` | `tests/user/` | `tests/conftest.py` |
| Persistence adapters | `tests/` | `tests/database/` | — | — | `tests/database/conftest.py` |
| UV tool / client lib | `testing/` | `testing/unit/` | `testing/integration/` | `testing/user/` | `testing/conftest.py` |

- Rule: One test module per subject — never put two unrelated subjects in the same file (e.g. do not mix config singleton tests with gRPC servicer tests).
- Rule: Use subfolders for parent/child groupings — e.g. `tests/unit/test_app_config_store.py`, `tests/integration/test_http_auth_server.py`.
- Rule: Name modules `test_<subject>.py` and functions `test_<behavior>_<expected>()`.
- Rule: Put cross-cutting non-fixture helpers in `tests/support/` (microservices) or `testing/helpers.py` (tools) — do not import from `conftest.py` modules.
- Rule: Register project-local pytest plugins (e.g. result table reporter) in `[tool.pytest.ini_options] plugins = [...]`.

### Test types — objectives and scope

Apply when deciding what kind of test to write for a change.

- Knowledge: **Unit tests** — fast, isolated; mock I/O boundaries; cover validation, error mapping, pure helpers, single-class behavior, and `Result` success/failure paths.
- Knowledge: **Integration tests** — multi-layer wiring without external network when possible; e.g. servicer → application with mocked repositories, FastAPI routes → auth application with in-memory drivers.
- Knowledge: **Database tests** — repository semantics, pagination, record models; mock DynamoDB unless a change requires real persistence (moto/local) — then isolate in `tests/database/`.
- Knowledge: **User-case tests** (`tests/user/` or `testing/user/`) — exercise every meaningful user option, not only happy path; include invalid inputs, boundary values, missing required fields, type mismatches, and authorization failures.
- Rule: Validation ingress must have dedicated tests for mandatory fields, types, bounds, and error codes mapped to `AppError` / gRPC status / HTTP status.
- Rule: Service boundaries returning `Result[T, AppError]` must test both `Success` and `Failure` branches with explicit assertions on `code` and `message`.
- Rule: Plugin drivers (vault, IdP, storage backends) must have unit tests per driver plus factory wiring tests in integration.
- Rule: Config singleton (`app_config`) must have tests proving load-once semantics and fail-fast before init.

### Async gRPC / DynamoDB services

Apply to `*.svc/server/` packages (IAM, solutions, storage, notification, collaboration, document-storage, arch diagram agent, general AI agent).

- Rule: Unit tests mock `aioboto3` / repository ports — no real DynamoDB in unit tests.
- Rule: Integration tests exercise servicer dispatch with mocked `ServicerContext` and async repository mocks — verify RPC wiring and `context.abort` paths.
- Rule: Full-stack persistence tests are optional and isolated — use moto or local DynamoDB only when mocks cannot represent the behavior under change.
- Rule: Run `uv run ruff check --select ASYNC src` before merging transport or I/O changes — see **`.cursor/rules/python/python.mdc`**.

### Configuration and commands

Apply when documenting or running tests for a package.

- Rule: Configure `[tool.pytest.ini_options]` in the package `pyproject.toml` with `testpaths`, `pythonpath = ["src"]`, and `asyncio_mode = "auto"`.
- Rule: Run from the package root: `uv sync --dev && uv run pytest`.
- Rule: Run a single file: `uv run pytest tests/unit/test_<subject>.py -v`.
- Rule: Run one test: `uv run pytest tests/unit/test_<subject>.py::test_<name> -v`.
- Rule: Run by marker when used: `uv run pytest -m integration`.

### Single-test pattern — reference shape

Apply when authoring a new test module; agents should match this structure.

- Knowledge: Canonical unit test shape:

```python
"""Tests for <subject> — <one-line scope>."""

from __future__ import annotations

import pytest

from my_package.module import fn_under_test
from my_package.core.results import Failure, Success


def test_fn_returns_success_for_valid_input() -> None:
    """Happy path: valid input yields Success."""
    outcome = fn_under_test("ok")
    assert isinstance(outcome, Success)
    assert outcome.unwrap() == "expected"


def test_fn_returns_failure_for_invalid_input() -> None:
    """User case: invalid input yields Failure with validation code."""
    outcome = fn_under_test("")
    assert isinstance(outcome, Failure)
    assert outcome.failure().code == "validation"
```

- Rule: Every test function has a one-line docstring stating the scenario (becomes the **Description** column in the agent table).
- Rule: Prefer `@pytest.mark.parametrize` for user-case matrices instead of copy-pasted test bodies.

### Agent feedback table — mandatory output format

Apply after every test run when reporting results to the user or in handoff.

- Rule: Summarize pytest results as a markdown table with exactly these columns: `#`, `Test`, `Description`, `Comment`, `Status`.
- Rule: `Status` uses traffic-light icons only — 🟢 success, 🟡 partial (skipped/xfail/warn), 🔴 failure/error.
- Rule: `#` is a 1-based row index; `Test` is the pytest node short name; `Description` is the test docstring first line; `Comment` is failure excerpt or `passed`/`skipped`.
- Knowledge: Example table:

| # | Test | Description | Comment | Status |
|---:|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | test_init_loads_once | Second init returns cached instance | passed | 🟢 |
| 2 | test_raises_before_init | Access before init fails fast | passed | 🟢 |
| 3 | test_invalid_path | Missing file surfaces Failure | AssertionError: ... | 🔴 |

- Action: After `uv run pytest`, build this table from pytest output or the project `tests/support/result_table.py` plugin when present.
- Action: When tests fail, fix failures and re-run until the table is all 🟢 or explain remaining 🔴/🟡 rows.

### Coverage objectives

Apply when assessing whether testing is complete for a change.

- Rule: Aim to validate 100% of public behavior for the changed module — all user-case branches, not only happy path.
- Rule: New modules require matching new test modules in the correct subfolder before handoff.
- Rule: Do not list individual test names in package `README.md` — tests change often; document framework, layout, and run commands only.
- Rule: CI and local runs use the same `uv run pytest` entrypoint — no alternate runners.

